TY  - JOUR
T1  - Creating Policy Alternatives Using Stakeholder Values
AU  - Gregory, Robin
AU  - Keeney, Ralph L.
Y1  - 1994/08/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.40.8.1035
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.40.8.1035
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1035
EP  - 1048
VL  - 40
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Choices that require multiple stakeholders to balance conflicting objectives are among today's most controversial decisions. Although many techniques exist for helping decision makers to select among projects, little attention has been given to processes for identifying improved alternatives based on clearly articulated stakeholder values. In this paper we describe a general process to inform controversial social decisions by first structuring stakeholder objectives and then using this information to create policy alternatives. We also report the results of a workshop in Sabah, Malaysia which used the proposed approach as the basis for multiple stakeholder negotiations.
AB  - Choices that require multiple stakeholders to balance conflicting objectives are among today's most controversial decisions. Although many techniques exist for helping decision makers to select among projects, little attention has been given to processes for identifying improved alternatives based on clearly articulated stakeholder values. In this paper we describe a general process to inform controversial social decisions by first structuring stakeholder objectives and then using this information to create policy alternatives. We also report the results of a workshop in Sabah, Malaysia which used the proposed approach as the basis for multiple stakeholder negotiations.
